leads.lead_text: Petals and sepals acute or obtuse, usually <20 mm long
Petals and sepals acuminate, usually >20 mm long
Plant reproducing vegetatively, often forming dense colonies; leaf oblong-lanceolate, 3–20 mm wide; labellum mid-lobe larger than side lobes, lamina calli in 2 converging rows near bend
Plant not reproducing vegetatively, colonies sparse; leaf linear, 1–3 mm wide; labellum mid-lobe smaller than side lobes, lamina calli in 2–4 more or less parallel rows
Labellum tip elongate, covered with congested, sessile, dark crimson to black, shiny calli
Labellum tip acute or obtuse but not elongate, not with dark congested calli (but calli often scattered)
Dorsal sepal erect, recurved or somewhat incurved, but not hooded over column and labellum
Dorsal sepal strongly hooded over column and labellum
Flower almost entirely white except for orange calli and marginal teeth
Flower not as above
Labellum lateral lobes broad and rounded, marginal teeth short and broad (squarish); lateral sepals <12 mm long ±parallel
Labellum lateral lobes narrow, marginal teeth long and thin (finger-like); lateral sepals >15 mm long, diverging
Labellum with a bright orange recurved tip
Labellum tip not bright orange
Perianth segments <10 mm long; labellum with a prominent, stalked, orange gland on either side of the mid-lobe
Perianth segments >10 mm long; labellum without such a pair of glands
Labellum lamina lacking dark transverse bars; leaf densely hairy; east of Melbourne
Labellum lamina with dark purplish transverse bars; leaf almost glabrous; Anglesea area
Flower not opening; labellum mid-lobe entire; perianth segments 6–7 mm long
Flower opening normally; labellum mid-lobe entire or with short teeth or calli; perianth segments 5–20 mm long
Sepals <10 mm long
Sepals >10 mm long
Lateral sepals partially or wholly fused, sepals less than 3 times as long as broad; flower stem thick
Lateral sepals free or fused at base only, sepals more than 3 times as long as broad; flower stem slender
Lateral lobes of labellum with a triangular forward protruding apex embracing the column; exterior of perianth segments generally brownish all over; dry forest mainly north of the Main Divide
Lateral lobes of labellum not as above; exterior of perianth segments pinkish; more mesic forests
Lateral lobes of labellum with a triangular forward protruding apex embracing the column; exterior of perianth segments generally brownish all over; dry forest mainly north of the Main Divide
Lateral lobes of labellum not as above; outside of perianth segments greenish, pink or with central brownish band
Leaf usually less than half as long as flowering stem; dorsal sepal erect
Leaf often reaching lowest flower; dorsal sepal incurved
Lateral sepals free to the base; labellum white to pale pink with darker pink transverse bars; common, widespread, variable species
Lateral sepals often fused at base; labellum deep pink with darker reddish transverse bars; rare species from the south-west
Flowers pink; ovary not swollen prior to fertilization, less than 10 mm long; lateral lobes of labellum entire; lateral sepals often fused at base
Flowers dull greenish-white; ovary usually swollen and more than 10 mm long; lateral lobes of labellum with a few marginal calli near mid-lobe; lateral sepals free
Leaf 5–8 mm wide, thick and fleshy; dorsal sepal 4–8 mm wide; alpine and subalpine forest, woodland and grassland in eastern Victoria, and higher parts of the Grampians
Leaf less than 5 mm wide, thin-textured; dorsal sepal 2–5 mm wide; plants mostly from low altitudes
Flowers greenish, yellow, brownish, dusky red or purplish
Flowers white or pink
Tips of petals and lateral sepals recurved; labellum not 3-lobed
Tips of petals and lateral sepals not recurved; labellum strongly 3-lobed
Flowers golden yellow, appearing in summer; plants to 30 cm tall; Otways only
Flowers not golden yellow, appearing in spring; plants to 25 cm tall; widespread
Flowers cream to greenish with some reddish suffusions or brownish or reddish purple; perianth segments to 15 mm long; mostly in the Grampians
Flowers cream to greenish; perianth segments to 10 mm long; widespread
Labellum obviously 3-lobed; flowers mostly white
Labellum virtually unlobed; flowers mostly white or pink
Flowers strongly musk-scented; lateral sepals and petals often drooping; labellum mid-lobe purplish towards the tip
Flowers not musk-scented; lateral sepals and petals stiffly spreading often with upturned tips; labellum mid-lobe entirely purplish
Flowers mostly white; outer surface of petals and sepals covered with reddish glandular hairs; flowers mostly August to September; widespread

Flowers mostly pale pink, sepals and petals often darker pink towards the apices; outer surface of petals and sepals with white to pale pink glandular hairs; flowers mostly September to November; east from about Sale
Column lacking yellow basal glands; labellum lamina calli in 2 rows
Column with 2 yellow basal glands; labellum lamina calli in 4–6 rows
Petals and sepals usually <25 mm long, broad at base tapering abruptly to short narrow tips
Petals and sepals usually >25 mm long, very narrow throughout
Flowers predominantly greyish cream to creamy white; labellum lamina calli in 5–9 pairs; flower stem usually 5–15 cm tall
Flowers predominantly red; labellum lamina calli in 10–16 pairs; flower stem usually 30–45 cm tall
Labellum lateral lobes green, with short or long comb-like teeth; labellum mid-lobe red
Labellum lateral lobes not usually green, or if greenish the margins entire; labellum mid-lobe variously coloured
Labellum lobes with teeth less than 1.5 mm long
Labellum lobes with teeth >2 mm long
Flower stem 8–20 cm tall; lateral sepals and petals strongly deflexed near ovary; labellum margins with numerous teeth; far western Victoria in woodland and mallee
Flower stem 6–10 cm tall; lateral sepals and petals spreading to obliquely deflexed; labellum margins with 3–5 pairs of teeth; extremely rare in north-east outskirts of Melbourne
Perianth segments not clubbed, less than 3 cm long
Sepals and often petals clubbed, usually more than 3 cm long
Lateral sepals pliant, often with an elbow-like bend near midway and curved upwards (often with drooping tips); labellum tremulous, marginal teeth rising above the level of the anther tip
Lateral sepals more or less straight and stiff; labellum not or slightly tremulous, marginal teeth not rising above the level of the anther tip
Sepals with bright yellow clubs; labellum laminar calli with verrucose heads; apparently restricted to sandy, semi-arid areas of north-western Victoria
Sepals with orange, red or brown clubs; labellum laminar calli with smooth heads
Labellum (when flattened) more than 18 mm long and wide; sepal clubs less than 9 mm long; apparently confined to sandy loams in the Little Desert area
Labellum (when flattened) less than 18 mm long and wide; sepal clubs 6–15 mm long
Leaf densely villous; flower stem thick; apparently confined to grassy Eucalyptus camaldulensis woodlands in the Stawell region
Leaf not densely villous; flower stem slender; widespread
Petals never clubbed (but sometimes with a few scattered glands); perianth segments 3–4 cm long; labellum 10–15 mm long (when flattened), lamina calli well-spaced; flowers Sep.–Nov.
Petals usually clubbed; perianth segments 4–6 cm long; labellum 14–17 mm long (when flattened), lamina calli densely crowded; flowers Nov.–Jan.
Labellum margins entire or nearly so
Labellum margins with few to many pairs of marginal teeth
Perianth segments to 25 mm long; labellum with thickened apical margins
Perianth segments >25 mm long; labellum without thickened apical margins
Labellum laminar calli in 2 or 4 very dense rows throughout; western Victoria
Labellum laminar calli in 4 or 6 dense rows, often becoming less dense on labellum mid-lobe; eastern Victoria
Flowers entirely greenish yellow except for reddish sepaline thickened clubs
Flowers not as above
Perianth segments erect; labellum 5–7 mm wide
Perianth segments spreading or obliquely deflexed; labellum >7 mm wide
Sepals, and often the petals, terminated by a clearly differentiated thickened club of tightly packed glands
Sepals and petals often glandular in distal half, but not terminated by a clearly differentiated thickened club of tightly packed glands
Flowers entirely dark red to crimson; lateral sepals and petals stiffly spreading
Flowers not as above
Flowers mostly greenish yellow, sometimes labellum mid-lobe and/or lamina calli reddish
Flowers not as above
Labellum unlobed, more or less flat; flowers appearing in September; lowland woodlands of western Victoria
Labellum obscurely 3-lobed, side lobes raised; flowers appearing in December; montane and sub-alpine woodlands of north-eastern Victoria
Flowers mostly white or creamy white; labellum laminar calli and marginal teeth often pink or reddish;  clubs reddish brown to black
Flowers not as above
Labellum margins with few short teeth <1 mm long, or almost entire;  flower stem to 15 cm tall, thick; extremely rare in the Bannockburn area only
Labellum margins with many teeth >1 mm long; flower stem usually >15 cm tall, slender
Sepaline clubs often very dark red to almost black, 10–22 mm long; south-west Victoria only
Sepaline clubs reddish brown, 6–12 mm long; known from a single collection on the Mornington Peninsula and possibly extinct
Labellum unlobed, more or less flat
Labellum with somewhat raised lateral lobes
Plants from low altitude near coastal areas; flowers appearing mostly the season following fires
Plants from higher altitude inland areas; flowering not dependent upon fires
Labellum with generally less than 10 pairs of marginal teeth
Labellum with (9–) 10 or more pairs of marginal teeth
Sepals and petals almost entirely cream or white; petals held in a elevated position in freshly opened flowers; near-coastal habitats and extremely rare
Sepals and petals not entirely cream or white; petals obliquely deflexed in freshly opened flowers; more inland habitats
Labellum lamina calli dull, not densely crowded; north-eastern Victoria only
Labellum lamina calli glossy, densely crowded; western Victoria only
Woodlands of the Little Desert area
Limestone outcrops near Portland
Lamina calli in 4 rows
At least some flowers with lamina calli in 6 rows
Plants of eastern Victoria, Briagolong area
Plants of western Victoria
Labellum with 9–12 pairs of marginal teeth; flowers yellow and red or entirely reddish; only known from the St Arnaud and Deep Lead areas of western Victoria
Labellum with 12–18 pairs of marginal teeth; flowers mostly creamy yellow; only known from the Dalyenong-Emu area of western Victoria
Flowering stem to 14 cm tall; leaf profusely hairy (base whitish due to abundant, broad hairs); probably extinct in Victoria, formerly occurring on the Otway Plain
Flowering stem on at least some plants >15 cm tall; leaf hairs not as above
Sepals on at least some flowers >45 mm long
Sepals <45 mm long
Flowering stem often >30 cm tall; lamina calli of labellum shiny; known only from French Island in Western Port
Flowering stem usually <30 cm tall; lamina calli of labellum not shiny; widespread in near-coastal areas
Sepals and petals spreading stiffly; far East Gippsland
Sepals and petals drooping in distal half
Petals usually lacking distinctly thickened clubs; known only from the Mornington Peninsula
Petals usually with distinctly thickened clubs
Flowers with a strong perfume reminiscent of burnt plastic; East Gippsland
Flowers not scented strongly; western Victoria
Labellum marginal teeth to 3.5 mm long, without thickened tips; flowers mostly white
Labellum marginal teeth to 2.5 mm long with thickened tips or absent; flowers variously coloured
Sepals 45–60 mm long; labellum to 10 mm wide
Sepals 60–100 mm long; labellum 10–15 mm wide
Sepals on all plants <40 mm long;
Sepals on at least some plants >40 mm long;
Labellum cordate with 4 dense rows of lamina calli on basal half of labellum, margins of mid-lobe thickened; south Gippsland
Labellum ovate with 4–6 moderately spaced rows of lamina calli extending on to mid-lobe, margins of mid-lobe not thickened
Flowers uniformly dark red to crimson; north-east Victoria
Flower colour not as above; western Victoria
Labellum margins entire or with short irregularly shaped teeth, lamina calli short, almost sessile; goldfields
Labellum margins with regularly shaped teeth, lamina calli prominently stalked
Flower uniformly purplish to blood-red
Flower variously coloured
Labellum with marginal teeth over most of its length; osmophore cells on sepals and petals in moniliform chains 3–4 cells long; south-west Victoria
Labellum with marginal teeth mostly on lateral lobes; osmophore cells on sepals and petals single or rarely in moniliform chains of 2 cells; Castlemaine area
Sepals >60 mm long in most plants
Sepals <60 mm long in most plants
Flowers usually cream, yellow or greenish-yellow, often with a reddish labellum mid-lobe
Flowers usually all pink or reddish or occasionally white with heavy pink striations or suffusions
Flowers greenish-yellow; labellum mid-lobe and lamina calli rarely red; flowers appearing in summer
Flowers cream or yellowish;  labellum mid-lobe often red; flowers appearing late winter and spring
Scape mostly >17 cm tall; flowers 1 or 2, not musk-scented, white, pink, red or purplish, sometimes with darker reddish striations; labellum lamina calli clubbed
Scape mostly <17 cm tall; flower single, musk-scented, pale to deep pink with darker pink striations or suffusions; labellum lamina calli finger-like
Flower solitary, mostly reddish; north-central Victoria
Flowers 1 or 2, white, pink, or purplish, sometimes with darker reddish striations; western Victoria
Lateral sepals and petals stiffly spreading; flowers mostly October to November
Lateral sepals and petals drooping; flowers mostly late August to September
Flowers mostly pale yellowish to white, sometimes with reddish labellum mid-lobe, calli and sepaline caudae
Flowers variously coloured, but not usually as above, labellum often entirely red or purplish on upper surface
Sepals often >90 mm long on at least some plants; flowers strongly scented; near coastal heath between Mornington Peninsula and Yarram
Sepals usually <80 mm long; flowers strongly scented or not
Flowers mostly white to creamy white; plants from inland open forests and woodlands
Flowers creamy yellow to greenish; plants mostly from near-coastal heathlands and heathy woodlands, or, very rare near Bendigo
Labellum white to creamy white with reddish lamina calli and marginal teeth; rare in open forest east of Melbourne
Labellum with strong reddish longitudinal streaks; north-east Victoria
Marginal teeth of labellum brown; glands near tips of sepals and petals closely-packed; south-west Victoria
Marginal teeth of labellum purple; glands near tips of sepals and petals not closely-packed, the underlying surface usually visible; very rare in Bendigo area
Labellum deep purplish; sepals to 100 mm long, stiffly spreading; known only from the goldfields north of Ballarat and presumed extinct
Labellum often reddish but not purplish; sepals to 80 mm long, drooping
Apical half to two-thirds of tepals dark reddish brown contrasting with bright coloured basal portion; known only from woodlands west of Geelong
Tepals not as above; goldfields near Stawell
